  "_about": "Eight FailureModes for the sulis-plugins-marketplace release-train Workflow. Three encode today's lived defects (CH-01KSYZ workflow-yaml-fails-to-parse, CH-01KSZ1 loop-guard-matches-founder-pr, GH-token tag bot-tag-doesnt-trigger-release-prod); one encodes the cycle-tolerance back-edge (release-pr-conflicts-with-target-at-merge — back-integrated twice in the project's history); the remaining four cover standard CI/PR failure surfaces + NFR-010 token-budget defense. Schema: plugins/sulis/brain/compiled/foundation/failuremode.schema.json. Tenant ULID is deterministic — derived as SHA256('tenant-name:sulis-plugins-marketplace') mapped to Crockford base32 (first char clamped to 0 per ULID spec); reused by every release-train canonical instance.",
  "captured_on": "2026-06-01",

  "failuremodes": [
    {
      "id": "dna:failuremode:01KTR2MXE6EA5XASA0C33S30VR",
      "sys_status": "active",
      "name": "release-pr-conflicts-with-target-at-merge",
      "for_domain": "dna:tenant:6XBZ93FSHN5TRX8MCS5R66FNCM",
      "kind": "business-logic-error",
      "description": "The release PR is mergeable=CONFLICTING at the moment release-on-merge attempts to merge it — the source branch (typically a release/* or change/* branch) diverged from the target (main or dev) since the PR opened, because another PR landed between open and merge. Recovery: back-integrate the target into the source (git merge target → push), wait for CI to re-green, retry from the open-pr Step. This is the cycle-tolerance back-edge that makes the workflow cycle-tolerant (lived twice in the project's history — encoded explicitly so future Step-authors do not assume linear-history).",
      "recovery_strategy": "escalate",
      "recovery_detail": "Surface CONFLICTING state to the founder via the release-train skill output. Founder back-integrates target into source manually (git checkout source; git merge target; push), waits for CI, re-runs release-on-merge. Future automation may automate the back-integration when target has only fast-forwardable commits, but the v1 stance is escalate-to-founder.",
      "expected_frequency": "occasional",
      "blocks_progress": true,
      "state": "active",
      "valid_from": "2026-06-01T00:00:00Z",
      "confidence": 0.9
    },
    {
      "id": "dna:failuremode:01KTR5NAFM3BGKRJTV1RTJD2MY",
      "sys_status": "active",
      "name": "workflow-yaml-fails-to-parse",
      "for_domain": "dna:tenant:6XBZ93FSHN5TRX8MCS5R66FNCM",
      "kind": "invalid-input",
      "description": "release-on-merge.yml fails to parse — typically because an inline shell snippet contains an unescaped colon or a heredoc that conflicts with YAML's flow syntax. CH-01KSYZ regression: PR #130 silently skipped because the YAML at HEAD didn't parse; GitHub Actions silently no-ops on parse failure. Recovery: abort the dispatch + surface the YAML parse error to the founder so the malformed file can be reverted or fixed.",
      "recovery_strategy": "abort",
      "recovery_detail": "Drift detector + branch-ci.yml MUST run pyyaml safe-load against release-on-merge.yml on every PR and fail the build on parse failure. This is the second line of defense; the first is the founder-typed lint at edit time. On parse failure: PR cannot land until release-on-merge.yml parses.",
      "expected_frequency": "rare",
      "blocks_progress": true,
      "state": "active",
      "valid_from": "2026-06-01T00:00:00Z",
      "confidence": 0.95
    },
    {
      "id": "dna:failuremode:01KTRA7VTSP3E14MZ4S641NHQ5",
      "sys_status": "active",
      "name": "loop-guard-matches-founder-pr",
      "for_domain": "dna:tenant:6XBZ93FSHN5TRX8MCS5R66FNCM",
      "kind": "policy-violation",
      "description": "release-on-merge's loop-guard regex (designed to skip its own previously-created release PRs to prevent infinite release-of-release-of-release loops) over-matches and skips a founder-authored PR whose title or body happens to contain the loop-guard's trigger pattern. CH-01KSZ1 regression: PR #132 was a founder PR that title-matched the bot's release-PR prefix and got skipped. Recovery: tighten the loop-guard regex (require bot-author or release-branch-prefix match in addition to title-prefix); abort the current dispatch when guard would skip a non-bot-authored PR.",
      "recovery_strategy": "abort",
      "recovery_detail": "Loop-guard regex MUST require BOTH (a) title-prefix match AND (b) actor=='github-actions[bot]' OR head_ref starts with 'release/'. Single-condition matches no longer skip. Drift detector verifies release-on-merge.yml encodes the both-conditions check.",
      "expected_frequency": "rare",
      "blocks_progress": true,
      "state": "active",
      "valid_from": "2026-06-01T00:00:00Z",
      "confidence": 0.95
    },
    {
      "id": "dna:failuremode:01KTRGB53ME08DPVBZ03RTS359",
      "sys_status": "active",
      "name": "bot-tag-doesnt-trigger-release-prod",
      "for_domain": "dna:tenant:6XBZ93FSHN5TRX8MCS5R66FNCM",
      "kind": "authorisation-denied",
      "description": "release-on-merge creates a git tag (v*.*.*) using GITHUB_TOKEN, but GitHub Actions' default GITHUB_TOKEN is denied permission to trigger downstream workflows (release-prod.yml) when pushing tags. This is a documented GitHub Actions security boundary, not a bug: bot-created refs do not fire workflow events by design. Recovery: fall back to a manual `gh release create` step that the founder runs to create the actual release artifact, OR swap GITHUB_TOKEN for a PAT (deferred — secret-management implication).",
      "recovery_strategy": "fallback",
      "recovery_detail": "release-on-merge.yml emits the tag + a journal entry instructing the founder to run `gh release create v<ver> --generate-notes`. The /sulis:release-train skill surfaces the deferred step in its summary. Future automation: PAT-scoped secret + bot identity rotation (deferred to a separate WP; out of scope for the canonical encoding).",
      "expected_frequency": "frequent",
      "blocks_progress": false,
      "state": "active",
      "valid_from": "2026-06-01T00:00:00Z",
      "confidence": 0.9
    },
    {
      "id": "dna:failuremode:01KTRS9GWHVX05E9VGM235NNXH",
      "sys_status": "active",
      "name": "pr-checks-fail",
      "for_domain": "dna:tenant:6XBZ93FSHN5TRX8MCS5R66FNCM",
      "kind": "business-logic-error",
      "description": "Required branch-protection status checks on the release PR fail (typically branch-ci.yml: pytest, drift detector, lint). Recovery: abort the dispatch, surface the failing check to the founder, do not auto-retry — a failing check means real work failed and re-running without changing inputs will produce the same failure.",
      "recovery_strategy": "abort",
      "recovery_detail": "release-on-merge polls the PR's check-runs API; on any failed required check, exits with the failed-check name + a link to the CI run log. Founder fixes the underlying issue (or reverts the offending commit) and reopens the release PR.",
      "expected_frequency": "occasional",
      "blocks_progress": true,
      "state": "active",
      "valid_from": "2026-06-01T00:00:00Z",
      "confidence": 0.92
    },
    {
      "id": "dna:failuremode:01KTRSHACB8X8VWV6GSAFPMDMF",
      "sys_status": "active",
      "name": "pr-open-but-mergeability-stuck",
      "for_domain": "dna:tenant:6XBZ93FSHN5TRX8MCS5R66FNCM",
      "kind": "infrastructure-failure",
      "description": "Release PR is open with all required checks green, but GitHub's mergeability state stays at 'UNKNOWN' or 'BLOCKED' indefinitely — typically because of a transient GitHub API hiccup that didn't recompute mergeability, OR a branch-protection setting changed mid-flight. The founder walked away assuming merge would auto-trigger; release stalls silently. Recovery: escalate via monitoring (cron-style poll detects mergeable=UNKNOWN for >N minutes and notifies the founder).",
      "recovery_strategy": "escalate",
      "recovery_detail": "release-on-merge does not retry forever; if mergeability is unknown after 3 polls (~6 minutes), exit with explicit 'mergeability stuck' status + ask the founder to recompute manually (close+reopen the PR forces a recompute on GitHub's side). The monitoring rule SHOULD page on the persistent-unknown state.",
      "expected_frequency": "rare",
      "blocks_progress": true,
      "state": "active",
      "valid_from": "2026-06-01T00:00:00Z",
      "confidence": 0.85
    },
    {
      "id": "dna:failuremode:01KTRNPG3DAPH7BW0CAQ05C3PH",
      "sys_status": "active",
      "name": "version-drift-detected-pre-flight",
      "for_domain": "dna:tenant:6XBZ93FSHN5TRX8MCS5R66FNCM",
      "kind": "policy-violation",
      "description": "Pre-flight check finds plugin.json.version disagrees with the matching entry in .claude-plugin/marketplace.json's plugins[].version, OR with the corresponding changeset's claimed version-bump. Typical cause: prior half-bump (a previous release-train run bumped plugin.json but failed before marketplace.json got updated, leaving the two artifacts out of sync). Recovery: abort the release; surface the specific version disagreement to the founder; founder reconciles (either manually re-running the failed sync step or accepting the version that's already shipped and bumping the other).",
      "recovery_strategy": "abort",
      "recovery_detail": "Pre-flight Step compares (plugin.json.version, marketplace.json[plugin].version, latest-changeset.version-bump-target). Three-way disagreement → abort with a table of the three values. Two-way disagreement (most common: plugin.json ahead, marketplace.json behind) → abort and tell founder to run the sync step manually.",
      "expected_frequency": "rare",
      "blocks_progress": true,
      "state": "active",
      "valid_from": "2026-06-01T00:00:00Z",
      "confidence": 0.9
    },
    {
      "id": "dna:failuremode:01KTRNKJ9DQSRREVTRTR82H95H",
      "sys_status": "active",
      "name": "probabilistic-step-token-budget-exceeded",
      "for_domain": "dna:tenant:6XBZ93FSHN5TRX8MCS5R66FNCM",
      "kind": "capacity-exceeded",
      "description": "An LLM-mechanism Step (specifically Step 5 'compose-changelog', the only probabilistic step in the release-train workflow per NFR-010) consumes its token budget before producing usable output. The budget is hard-capped in the canonical Step's token_budget field. Recovery: fall back to the deterministic template path (assemble CHANGELOG from the changeset summaries directly, without LLM synthesis); the result is less narrative but always ships.",
      "recovery_strategy": "fallback",
      "recovery_detail": "/sulis-brain:execute-workflow's budget-tracker surfaces the overflow; the imperative path in release-on-merge.yml MUST detect the same condition (LLM response truncated or budget API returns exhausted) and substitute the deterministic CHANGELOG-from-template generator. The drift detector verifies BOTH paths exist in the YAML — LLM Step + deterministic fallback under the same Step's annotation block.",
      "expected_frequency": "occasional",
      "blocks_progress": false,
      "state": "active",
      "valid_from": "2026-06-01T00:00:00Z",
      "confidence": 0.85
    }
  ]
